window.SECAI = window.SECAI || {}; SECAI.questions = SECAI.questions || [];
SECAI.questions.push(
  { id:"D1-001", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A SOC team needs to detect brand-new attack patterns that have never been labeled in their historical data. Which AI approach is best suited to discovering these previously unknown anomalies?", options:["Unsupervised learning","Supervised learning","Rule-based signature matching","A static allow-list"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Unsupervised learning</strong> uses unlabeled data to identify patterns and anomalies, so it excels at discovering previously unknown threats the team has never labeled.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Supervised learning</b>: requires labeled examples and struggles with novel attacks absent from its training phase.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based signature matching</b>: only catches threats matching predefined signatures, missing novel anomalies entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>A static allow-list</b>: permits known-good entries and does not learn or surface emerging anomalies at all.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-002", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"An analyst wants a model that learns to label emails as 'spam' or 'safe' using a dataset where every email is already tagged with the correct answer. Which learning approach does this describe?", options:["Reinforcement learning","Supervised learning","Unsupervised learning","Federated learning"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Supervised learning</strong> trains a model on a labeled dataset where each input is paired with a correct output, such as labeling emails as spam or safe, enabling high accuracy for phishing detection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reinforcement learning</b>: learns by trial and error using reward signals, not from a fixed set of pre-labeled examples.</span><span class='qd'><b>Unsupervised learning</b>: works on unlabeled data to find patterns, so it would not use the provided spam/safe labels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated learning</b>: describes where training happens across distributed clients, not whether the data is labeled.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-003", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A threat actor group wants to mass-produce highly realistic phishing emails and polymorphic malware that evades signature detection. Which AI capability is most directly being abused?", options:["Anomaly detection","Federated learning","Generative AI","K-fold cross-validation"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Generative AI</strong> creates new content by learning patterns from large datasets, and attackers abuse it to craft realistic phishing simulations, malware with unique signatures, and polymorphic code to evade detection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Anomaly detection</b>: identifies deviations from normal behavior and is a defensive technique, not a content-generation capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated learning</b>: is a distributed training method, not a way to generate phishing or malware content.</span><span class='qd'><b>K-fold cross-validation</b>: is a model evaluation technique used during development, not a generation capability.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-004", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A security researcher needs an architecture that excels at understanding how words in a phishing email relate to one another in sequence in order to classify malicious intent. Which technology is most appropriate?", options:["Isolation Forest","A simple decision tree","Logistic regression","Transformers"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Transformers</strong> are neural network architectures that focus on the connections between pieces of information in a sequence, such as how words in a sentence relate, making them highly effective for language tasks like phishing analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Isolation Forest</b>: is an unsupervised anomaly-detection algorithm for high-dimensional data, not a language-understanding architecture.</span><span class='qd'><b>Logistic regression</b>: is a simple linear classifier and does not model word-to-word sequence relationships.</span><span class='qd'><b>A simple decision tree</b>: splits on individual features and cannot capture contextual sequence relationships in text.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-005", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A SOC analyst wants to flag unusual login activity by isolating observations that are far from the norm in high-dimensional log data, even when the dataset has many outliers. Which unsupervised algorithm is best suited?", options:["Isolation Forest","Gradient-boosted decision trees","A GAN discriminator","A convolutional neural network"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Isolation Forest</strong> is an unsupervised algorithm that identifies anomalies in high-dimensional data by isolating observations far from the norm, and its resilience to outliers makes it ideal for detecting unusual login activity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A GAN discriminator</b>: distinguishes real from synthetic samples during generative training, not anomaly isolation in logs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Gradient-boosted decision trees</b>: are a supervised ensemble that requires labeled events rather than unsupervised isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A convolutional neural network</b>: is typically used on raw byte sequences or images, not lightweight outlier isolation.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-006", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An incident responder needs a model that can analyze the raw byte sequence of an executable to learn opcode and entropy patterns revealing whether a file is packed malware. Which technique is described?", options:["Clustering","Convolutional neural networks (CNNs)","Reinforcement learning","Retrieval-augmented generation"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Convolutional neural networks (CNNs)</strong> can analyze the raw byte sequence of an executable to automatically learn opcode and entropy patterns that reveal whether a file is legitimate or packed malware designed to slip past signature scanners.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Clustering</b>: groups similar events in unsupervised analysis and does not learn byte-level malware features for classification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reinforcement learning</b>: optimizes response actions via rewards, not static analysis of executable byte sequences.</span><span class='qd'><b>Retrieval-augmented generation</b>: pulls documents into context for a language model and does not classify binary opcode patterns.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-007", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A team trains an adaptive firewall agent that observes traffic, then chooses to allow, throttle, or block, earning +10 for blocking confirmed malware and -3 for a false positive. Which approach is in use?", options:["Supervised classification","Unsupervised clustering","Reinforcement learning","Federated averaging"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Reinforcement learning</strong> teaches an agent to decide actions like allow, rate-limit, or block on the fly, scoring decisions with reward signals such as +10 for blocked malware and penalties for false positives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Supervised classification</b>: maps labeled inputs to outputs and does not learn an action policy from reward signals.</span><span class='qd'><b>Unsupervised clustering</b>: groups similar data without labels or rewards and stops at detection, not action selection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated averaging</b>: aggregates model updates from distributed clients and is unrelated to reward-driven action choice.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-008", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A security appliance with very limited memory and CPU needs to classify alerts in real time at low latency and on-premises. Which model type best fits these constraints?", options:["A diffusion image model","A large language model (LLM) with hundreds of billions of parameters","A multi-GPU training cluster","A small language model (SLM)"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>A small language model (SLM)</strong> has low parameter counts, modest hardware needs, and emphasizes low latency and local operation, making it ideal for real-time alert classification on limited resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A large language model (LLM) with hundreds of billions of parameters</b>: requires substantial memory and high-end GPUs, unsuitable for a constrained appliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A multi-GPU training cluster</b>: is training infrastructure, not a deployable model for an embedded appliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A diffusion image model</b>: generates images and is irrelevant to low-latency text alert classification.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-009", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A red team wants to generate synthetic but realistic attack logs and new malware variants to test the resilience of ML-based defenses. Which architecture, built from two competing neural networks, is most appropriate?", options:["A generative adversarial network (GAN)","A transformer encoder","An autoencoder used alone","A logistic regression model"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A generative adversarial network (GAN)</strong> consists of two neural networks contesting each other, one generating synthetic samples and one distinguishing real from fake, making it powerful for creating realistic attack logs and malware variants for testing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A transformer encoder</b>: processes sequences for language tasks and is not the two-network adversarial generator described.</span><span class='qd'><b>An autoencoder used alone</b>: reconstructs inputs to flag anomalies and does not pit two networks against each other to synthesize data.</span><span class='qd'><b>A logistic regression model</b>: is a simple linear classifier with no generative capability.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-010", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An organization wants to analyze multi-layered patterns in network traffic to detect advanced persistent threats by learning directly from raw data rather than manually defined signatures. Which AI subset is described?", options:["Rule-based expert systems","Deep learning","Statistical learning regression","A signature-based IDS"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Deep learning</strong>, a subset of ML, uses multi-layered neural networks to learn complex patterns from raw data, letting it detect APTs and recognize previously unseen threats without manually defined signatures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based expert systems</b>: rely on explicitly programmed rules and cannot learn subtle patterns directly from raw data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Statistical learning regression</b>: underpins ML but typically uses shallow mathematical models rather than multi-layered networks.</span><span class='qd'><b>A signature-based IDS</b>: depends on manually defined signatures and struggles with previously unseen threats.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-011", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A security team must process huge volumes of unstructured text from logs, threat reports, and emails to extract indicators of compromise and detect phishing intent. Which AI branch is most directly applicable?", options:["Reinforcement learning","Image classification","Natural language processing (NLP)","Data balancing"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Natural language processing (NLP)</strong> enables computers to understand and analyze large amounts of natural language data, helping security teams process unstructured text, extract IOCs from reports, and detect phishing intent.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Image classification</b>: categorizes visual data, not unstructured text from logs and reports.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reinforcement learning</b>: learns action policies via rewards and is not focused on language comprehension.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data balancing</b>: realigns class proportions in training sets and does not interpret text meaning.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-012", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A model trained only on historical phishing examples repeatedly fails to flag a brand-new attack technique it never saw. Which weakness of supervised learning does this illustrate?", options:["It cannot process structured data","It only works on images","It requires no labeled data","It struggles with novel threats not present during training"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>It struggles with novel threats not present during training</strong> correctly captures that supervised models trained solely on historical data may fail to recognize emerging attacks that were not included in their training phase.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It cannot process structured data</b>: supervised learning handles structured data well; that is not the weakness here.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires no labeled data</b>: the opposite is true, supervised learning depends heavily on labeled examples.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only works on images</b>: supervised learning applies broadly to text, logs, and many data types, not only images.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-013", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"During model validation, an engineer splits data into k equal folds, trains k times each holding out one fold, then averages the test scores. What is the primary benefit of this k-fold cross-validation?", options:["It makes evaluation less dependent on any single lucky or unlucky data split","It guarantees the model will never overfit","It eliminates the need for a training set","It encrypts the dataset at rest"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It makes evaluation less dependent on any single lucky or unlucky data split</strong> describes k-fold cross-validation, where averaging across k runs gives a more reliable estimate of generalization than one fixed split.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees the model will never overfit</b>: cross-validation helps detect overfitting but cannot guarantee its absence.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for a training set</b>: each fold still uses k-1 folds for training, so a training set is always needed.</span><span class='qd'><b>It encrypts the dataset at rest</b>: cross-validation is an evaluation method, not an encryption control.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-014", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A spam classifier performs perfectly on its training logs but fails badly on new traffic. Which problem, in which a model memorizes training data and fails to generalize, is most likely?", options:["Underfitting","Overfitting","Concept drift","Quantization"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Overfitting</strong> occurs when a model memorizes its training data and fails to generalize, producing excellent results on training records but poor performance on new, unseen data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Underfitting</b>: happens when a model learns too little and performs poorly even on training data, not perfectly on it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Concept drift</b>: is when real-world data slowly changes over time, not memorization of a fixed training set.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization</b>: reduces numeric precision of weights for efficiency and is unrelated to generalization failure.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-015", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"Spammers gradually adopt new keywords over months, causing a deployed model's accuracy to slowly degrade as the real-world data shifts. Which phenomenon does this describe?", options:["Data balancing","Overfitting","Concept drift","One-hot encoding"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Concept drift</strong> is when the kinds of real-world data a model sees slowly change over time, for example spammers adopting new keywords, gradually degrading performance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Overfitting</b>: refers to memorizing training data, not a gradual shift in incoming real-world data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data balancing</b>: realigns class proportions in a training set and does not describe evolving live data.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-hot encoding</b>: is a method to convert categorical text into numeric form, unrelated to performance drift.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-016", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An adversary subtly manipulates training data to embed hidden vulnerabilities that only surface later in production. Which attack does keeping training, validation, and test sets strictly separate help detect?", options:["Cryptographic key exhaustion","Distributed denial-of-service","Cross-site scripting","Silent data-poisoning attacks"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Silent data-poisoning attacks</strong> involve adversaries subtly manipulating training data to embed hidden vulnerabilities, and keeping data sets strictly separate gives teams a clear view to detect such covert manipulation before production.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Distributed denial-of-service</b>: floods a service with traffic and is not detected by separating training data partitions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-site scripting</b>: is a web-injection attack unrelated to ML dataset partitioning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic key exhaustion</b>: concerns key management limits, not poisoned training data detection.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-017", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A security team auto-tags raw logs with indicators from threat-intel feeds, YARA/Sigma rules, and sandbox verdicts to speed up labeling. What is a key risk of this weak supervision approach?", options:["It can introduce label noise, leading to inaccurate or conflicting tags and bias","It makes labeling impossibly slow","It requires no data at all","It permanently encrypts all labels"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It can introduce label noise, leading to inaccurate or conflicting tags and bias</strong> is the key risk of weak supervision, which can cause over-flagging of benign activity or missed novel attacks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It makes labeling impossibly slow</b>: weak supervision actually speeds up data curation, the opposite of slowing it down.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires no data at all</b>: it still operates on raw logs and auto-generated tags, so data is required.</span><span class='qd'><b>It permanently encrypts all labels</b>: weak supervision generates labels and has nothing to do with encryption.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-018", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"To reduce the influence of labels from lower-trust sources during weak supervision, a team statistically down-weights those labels. Which safeguard is this?", options:["Quantization","Confidence weighting","Data augmentation","Federated averaging"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Confidence weighting</strong> reduces the statistical influence of labels from lower-trust sources, helping maintain the reliability of weakly supervised training data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization</b>: lowers numeric precision of model weights for efficiency, not label trust weighting.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data augmentation</b>: generates additional training examples and does not adjust label trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated averaging</b>: aggregates client model updates and is unrelated to weighting individual label sources.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-019", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An SOC has no reliable labels during a zero-day hunt and wants to learn what 'normal' looks like, then flag sharp deviations. Which unsupervised technique groups events sharing similar IP pairs, ports, and session durations?", options:["Gradient boosting","Logistic regression","Clustering","Supervised fine-tuning"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Clustering</strong> groups events that naturally share characteristics such as similar IP pairs, port combinations, and session durations, mapping everyday behavior so genuinely strange activity stands out.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Gradient boosting</b>: is a supervised ensemble that needs labeled events, unavailable in this zero-day scenario.</span><span class='qd'><b>Logistic regression</b>: is a supervised classifier requiring labels, not unsupervised grouping.</span><span class='qd'><b>Supervised fine-tuning</b>: adapts a model using labeled task data, which the team lacks here.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-020", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A team trains small neural networks to recreate the records they see during learning so that a high reconstruction error later flags abnormal events. Which technique is described?", options:["Differential privacy","Decision trees","One-shot prompting","Autoencoders"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Autoencoders</strong> are small neural networks trained to recreate the records they see, learning a model of normalcy so that a high reconstruction error signals activity outside the learned baseline.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Decision trees</b>: split data on feature thresholds and do not reconstruct inputs to measure error.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-shot prompting</b>: gives a model a single example in a prompt and is unrelated to reconstruction-based anomaly detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy</b>: adds calibrated noise to protect individuals and is not a reconstruction technique.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-021", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"After a reinforcement learning security agent finishes training, the team deploys it so it only posts recommendations beside human analyst decisions without enforcing them. What is this phase called?", options:["Shadow mode","Autonomous mode","Pre-training","Quantization mode"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Shadow mode</strong> deploys the agent so it does not enforce its choices but merely posts recommendations alongside human analyst actions, allowing side-by-side comparison before full automation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Autonomous mode</b>: is when the agent acts on its own after proving itself, not the non-enforcing observation phase.</span><span class='qd'><b>Pre-training</b>: builds a base model on a massive general dataset and precedes deployment entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization mode</b>: is not a deployment phase; quantization reduces model numeric precision.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-022", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team takes a model already trained on a large general dataset and further trains it on a small dataset specific to identifying malicious user activity. Which technique builds on transfer learning this way?", options:["Pre-training from scratch","Fine-tuning","Data balancing","Tenant isolation"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Fine-tuning</strong> builds on transfer learning by taking a pre-trained model and further training it on a smaller task-specific dataset, specializing it while benefiting from broad prior knowledge.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pre-training from scratch</b>: trains a large model on a massive general dataset and is the step fine-tuning comes after, not the specialization itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data balancing</b>: adjusts class proportions and is not a transfer-learning specialization technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tenant isolation</b>: separates customers' data in shared systems and is a security control, not a training method.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-023", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A team fine-tunes a model and notices that using too many epochs causes it to learn noise and perform poorly on new examples. What is happening, and what does the number of epochs measure?", options:["Underfitting; epochs measure dataset size","Pruning; epochs measure GPU count","Overfitting; epochs measure how many times the model processes the entire dataset","Quantization; epochs measure bit precision"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Overfitting; epochs measure how many times the model processes the entire dataset</strong> is correct because too many epochs cause the model to learn noise and specific details, hurting performance on unseen data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Underfitting; epochs measure dataset size</b>: too few epochs cause underfitting, and epochs count passes over data, not dataset size.</span><span class='qd'><b>Pruning; epochs measure GPU count</b>: pruning removes unimportant weights and epochs are not a GPU count.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization; epochs measure bit precision</b>: quantization changes numeric precision and epochs do not measure bit precision.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-024", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"To deploy a model on a resource-constrained mobile device, a team removes weights that have a negligible impact on performance to shrink the model and speed up inference. Which technique is this?", options:["Watermarking","Data augmentation","Federated averaging","Pruning"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Pruning</strong> removes less important elements such as low-impact weights to reduce model size and improve inference speed while maintaining accuracy, which is especially useful for resource-constrained devices.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data augmentation</b>: generates additional training examples and does not shrink the model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated averaging</b>: aggregates distributed client updates and does not remove weights for size reduction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Watermarking</b>: embeds identifiers for ownership tracking and does not reduce model size.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-025", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"To save memory and speed predictions, a team converts a model's weights from 32-bit floating-point numbers to 8-bit integers. Which technique is this, and what helps preserve accuracy during the shift?", options:["Quantization; quantization-aware training","Pruning; weak supervision","Augmentation; downsampling","Fine-tuning; one-hot encoding"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Quantization; quantization-aware training</strong> is correct because quantization converts high-precision weights to lower-precision formats like 8-bit integers, and quantization-aware training helps preserve the model's effectiveness during that shift.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pruning; weak supervision</b>: pruning removes weights rather than changing precision, and weak supervision is an auto-labeling method.</span><span class='qd'><b>Augmentation; downsampling</b>: both are data-set techniques, not weight-precision conversion.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fine-tuning; one-hot encoding</b>: fine-tuning adapts a model and one-hot encoding converts categories, neither describes precision reduction.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-026", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A hospital consortium wants to train a shared model without ever moving patient data off each hospital's devices, sending only model updates back to a central server. Which approach is this?", options:["Centralized batch training","Federated learning","Retrieval-augmented generation","Supervised fine-tuning"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Federated learning</strong> keeps data on client devices and sends only model parameters and updates back to a central server, addressing privacy and regulatory concerns by sending the AI to the data rather than the data to the AI.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Centralized batch training</b>: gathers all data in one location, the opposite of keeping data on client devices.</span><span class='qd'><b>Retrieval-augmented generation</b>: pulls documents into a model's context at inference time and is not a distributed training method.</span><span class='qd'><b>Supervised fine-tuning</b>: adapts a model on labeled data but says nothing about keeping data decentralized.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-027", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"In a federated learning deployment, the team worries that model updates shared with the server could leak data through inference attacks. Which technique encrypts client updates so the server only sees the combined average?", options:["Pruning","One-hot encoding","Secure aggregation","Concept drift correction"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Secure aggregation</strong> encrypts each user's data and only decrypts when enough updates are combined, revealing only the average of all updates so the server never sees a single user's data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>One-hot encoding</b>: converts categorical fields to numeric form and provides no privacy for model updates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Pruning</b>: removes low-impact weights to shrink a model and does not protect update privacy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Concept drift correction</b>: addresses changing data distributions, not the confidentiality of federated updates.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-028", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A federated learning system adds carefully calibrated noise so each individual client's contribution is hidden while overall results stay accurate. Which privacy technique is this?", options:["Watermarking","Tenant isolation","Rate limiting","Differential privacy"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Differential privacy</strong> adds carefully calibrated noise to data so each individual's contribution is hidden while the overall results remain useful and accurate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tenant isolation</b>: separates one customer's data from another's and does not add noise to hide individual contributions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rate limiting</b>: throttles request volume to slow abuse and is unrelated to statistical noise injection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Watermarking</b>: embeds traceable identifiers and does not obscure individual data contributions.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-029", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A federated learning team observes that a few client devices hold far more data than the others, skewing the global model toward those data-heavy devices. Which federated learning challenge does this represent?", options:["Device heterogeneity causing model drift","Communication overhead","Quantization error","Prompt injection"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Device heterogeneity causing model drift</strong> is correct because devices with more data skew the learning toward those data-heavy devices, creating a balancing issue that can lead to model drift.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Communication overhead</b>: concerns bandwidth and latency from frequent client-server messaging, not data imbalance across devices.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization error</b>: arises from lowering numeric precision of weights, unrelated to uneven client data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Prompt injection</b>: is a language-model input attack, not a federated data-balancing problem.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-030", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"An SOC analyst wants the model to behave as a specific persona, such as a SOC analyst that always returns JSON, by setting a compact statement at the start of every session. Which prompt element defines this?", options:["A multi-shot example","The system role","A vector index","The reward function"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>The system role</strong> is a compact statement that defines the model's persona, scope, and formatting discipline, such as acting as a SOC analyst and returning structured JSON.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A multi-shot example</b>: provides several labeled samples to guide output but does not set the model's overall persona.</span><span class='qd'><b>A vector index</b>: stores text embeddings for retrieval and is unrelated to defining a persona.</span><span class='qd'><b>The reward function</b>: scores actions in reinforcement learning and has nothing to do with prompt personas.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-031", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An analyst pastes a raw YARA rule and asks the model whether it would catch a new ransomware strain, providing no prior examples. Which prompting technique is being used?", options:["Multi-shot prompting","One-shot prompting","Zero-shot prompting","Template injection"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Zero-shot prompting</strong> supplies no prior examples and asks the model to reason directly, generating fast, creative insight useful when historical data is unavailable during early incident response.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Multi-shot prompting</b>: provides several labeled examples, but here none are supplied.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-shot prompting</b>: provides exactly one labeled example, which is not the case in a no-example request.</span><span class='qd'><b>Template injection</b>: is not a prompting technique; templates inject telemetry into placeholders.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-032", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team supplies one labeled benign NetFlow record, then presents a second record and asks the model to classify it. What is a notable risk of this one-shot approach?", options:["It consumes the most tokens of any technique","It cannot return JSON","It requires a full ML pipeline","It may overfit to the single example so an atypical record generalizes poorly"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>It may overfit to the single example so an atypical record generalizes poorly</strong> is the documented risk of one-shot prompting, since if the lone record is atypical the model generalizes poorly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It consumes the most tokens of any technique</b>: one-shot keeps token costs low; multi-shot consumes more tokens.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires a full ML pipeline</b>: one-shot prompting deliberately avoids building a full ML pipeline.</span><span class='qd'><b>It cannot return JSON</b>: prompting techniques can request structured JSON output regardless of shot count.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-033", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A team feeds ten labeled Suricata alerts (five benign, five malicious) and asks the model to label a new batch, approximating supervised learning. What is the main downside of this multi-shot approach?", options:["It consumes more tokens and may unintentionally reveal proprietary indicators or customer IP ranges","It provides no operational value","It cannot reach useful precision","It only works on images"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It consumes more tokens and may unintentionally reveal proprietary indicators or customer IP ranges</strong> is the key risk of multi-shot prompting, which is why teams should redact sensitive fields and monitor prompt size.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It provides no operational value</b>: multi-shot approximates supervised learning and often reaches high triage precision.</span><span class='qd'><b>It cannot reach useful precision</b>: multi-shot can reach 80% or more precision in triage tasks.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only works on images</b>: it is applied to text artifacts like Suricata alerts, not only images.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-034", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team manages reusable prompt files in Git with placeholders like {log_lines} that an automation layer fills with real telemetry at runtime. Which benefit do these prompt templates provide?", options:["They eliminate the need for any data","They guarantee consistent field names and formats so downstream parsers do not break","They replace the model entirely","They make outputs intentionally random"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>They guarantee consistent field names and formats so downstream parsers do not break</strong> is a core benefit of templates, ensuring dashboards and log parsers that depend on predictable data keep working.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They eliminate the need for any data</b>: templates inject real telemetry into placeholders, so data is still required.</span><span class='qd'><b>They replace the model entirely</b>: templates structure prompts sent to the model; they do not replace it.</span><span class='qd'><b>They make outputs intentionally random</b>: templates promote consistency, the opposite of randomness.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-035", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"Before sending telemetry containing internal hostnames and client IPs to a public model, a team swaps sensitive values for consistent, format-preserving tokens. Why preserve the structure during tokenization?", options:["To increase token cost deliberately","To make the data unreadable to the model","To preserve structural relationships the model needs to reason accurately while hiding confidential data","To bypass the system role"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>To preserve structural relationships the model needs to reason accurately while hiding confidential data</strong> is correct because tokenized replacements mimic genuine log structure so the model can still reason without exposing real values.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To make the data unreadable to the model</b>: the goal is preserved structure for accurate reasoning, not unreadability.</span><span class='qd'><b>To increase token cost deliberately</b>: tokenization protects data, not to raise costs on purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>To bypass the system role</b>: tokenization sanitizes data and does not circumvent the system role.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-036", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"An attacker hides a string inside an HTML alt tag that manipulates a help-desk LLM into 'dump the entire customer database.' This is most analogous to which traditional web attack?", options:["Brute-force password guessing","TCP SYN flood","ARP spoofing","SQL injection"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>SQL injection</strong> is the stated analogy: prompt security must account for hostile inputs just as web security accounts for SQL injection, where a crafted input tricks a system into running unintended commands.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>TCP SYN flood</b>: exhausts connection resources and is not an injection of unintended instructions.</span><span class='qd'><b>ARP spoofing</b>: poisons address resolution on a local network, unrelated to manipulating model instructions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Brute-force password guessing</b>: tries many credentials and does not embed malicious instructions in input.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-037", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"To stop an attacker who gains interactive access from making the model produce shell commands, a team adds a sentence to the system prompt restricting that behavior to admins. Which control is this?", options:["A policy filter embedded in the system prompt","Cryptographic watermarking","Rate limiting","Differential privacy"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A policy filter embedded in the system prompt</strong> adds an instruction such as rejecting requests to produce shell commands unless the user role equals admin, preventing privilege escalation even with interactive access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic watermarking</b>: verifies output origin and integrity but does not gate which commands the model produces.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rate limiting</b>: throttles request volume and does not restrict command generation by role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy</b>: adds noise to protect individuals and is unrelated to command-restriction policy.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-038", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team deploys a tool that sits between user input and the model, inspecting both the prompt and the draft response against JSON schemas and regex allow-lists before returning output. What is this?", options:["A vector store","A guardrail framework","A model registry","A reward shaping function"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>A guardrail framework</strong> acts as a protective layer between user input and model output, checking both against rules such as JSON schemas or regex allow-lists to ensure only safe, well-formatted responses are returned.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A vector store</b>: holds embeddings for retrieval and does not inspect or filter prompts and responses.</span><span class='qd'><b>A model registry</b>: is an auditable record of model and dataset versions, not a runtime input/output filter.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reward shaping function</b>: guides reinforcement learning and does not validate prompts against schemas.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-039", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A SIEM needs to confirm that an LLM-generated alert genuinely came from an authorized model and was not tampered with after leaving it. Which control provides this assurance?", options:["Downsampling","One-hot encoding","Cryptographic watermarks and signed responses","A canary release"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Cryptographic watermarks and signed responses</strong> are hidden, hard-to-forge markers that let downstream systems verify a response genuinely originated from an authorized AI model and was not altered after leaving it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>One-hot encoding</b>: converts categorical features to numeric form and provides no integrity verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Downsampling</b>: reduces majority-class records for balancing and offers no authenticity assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A canary release</b>: gradually rolls out a change to a subset and does not verify message origin.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-040", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"To slow brute-force prompt probing that tries to guess instructions, a team sets a limit of 10 requests per minute per API key and records every request with timestamps and source IPs. Which two controls are combined?", options:["Augmentation and balancing","Pruning and quantization","Clustering and regression","Rate limiting and exhaustive audit logging"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Rate limiting and exhaustive audit logging</strong> combine throttling at the API gateway to slow brute-force prompt probing with detailed logs that create a forensic timeline for incident responders.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pruning and quantization</b>: are model-efficiency techniques, not request throttling or logging.</span><span class='qd'><b>Clustering and regression</b>: are learning methods unrelated to gateway controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Augmentation and balancing</b>: are dataset-preparation techniques, not abuse-prevention controls.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-041", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team needs to push fresh internal incident-report knowledge into a model's answers without retraining it, by retrieving relevant documents and using them as context. Which approach fits and requires no training?", options:["Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)","Pre-training from scratch","Reinforcement learning","Quantization-aware training"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)</strong> requires no training; the model retrieves relevant documents and uses them as context to answer prompts, keeping the foundation model unchanged while pushing fresh knowledge into vector storage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pre-training from scratch</b>: trains a large model on massive data and is impractical for each document update.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reinforcement learning</b>: trains an action policy via rewards and does not inject retrieved documents at inference.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization-aware training</b>: preserves accuracy while reducing precision and is unrelated to retrieval.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-042", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A junior analyst asks why generative AI outputs are sometimes confidently wrong, producing fabricated indicators. What is this behavior commonly called, and what guardrail practice helps?", options:["Overfitting; deleting the training set","Hallucination; pairing NLP with input/output filtering and human approval for high-risk actions","Concept drift; increasing temperature","Quantization; adding more GPUs"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Hallucination; pairing NLP with input/output filtering and human approval for high-risk actions</strong> is correct because models can hallucinate or be prompt-injected, so organizations pair NLP with guardrails and keep high-risk actions behind human approval.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Overfitting; deleting the training set</b>: overfitting is memorization of training data, and deleting the set is not a mitigation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Concept drift; increasing temperature</b>: drift is changing data over time, and raising temperature increases randomness rather than reducing fabrication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization; adding more GPUs</b>: quantization reduces precision and GPUs add compute, neither addresses fabricated outputs.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-043", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An organization wants the LLM to output event_time, src_ip, dst_ip, and alert_priority so a SIEM can ingest results through one rule without custom parsers. Which formatting discipline supports this?", options:["Returning raw packet hex dumps","Returning free-form prose paragraphs","Returning structured JSON with a consistent field schema","Returning randomly ordered fields each time"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Returning structured JSON with a consistent field schema</strong> lets SIEM and SOAR tools ingest model output immediately because all tools share the same JSON keys, avoiding error-prone custom parsing code.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Returning free-form prose paragraphs</b>: cannot be reliably ingested by automated tools that expect fixed fields.</span><span class='qd'><b>Returning raw packet hex dumps</b>: is not a structured, schema-defined format for SIEM ingestion.</span><span class='qd'><b>Returning randomly ordered fields each time</b>: breaks parsers and dashboards that depend on predictable structure.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-044", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team wants the same raw firewall logs reinterpreted for a non-technical executive briefing in under 200 words with no jargon, then later for a PCI-DSS compliance mapping. What primarily enables these different outputs?", options:["Re-encrypting the dataset","Retraining the model for each audience","Changing the GPU hardware","Adjusting only the system role while submitting the same underlying event data"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Adjusting only the system role while submitting the same underlying event data</strong> lets practitioners from analysts to executives receive answers calibrated to their responsibilities, aligning the model's tone, depth, and format.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Retraining the model for each audience</b>: is unnecessary and impractical; only the role changes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Changing the GPU hardware</b>: affects performance, not the audience-tailored framing of output.</span><span class='qd'><b>Re-encrypting the dataset</b>: protects data at rest and does not reshape the model's response style.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-045", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"An effective user prompt blends three elements: the evidence to inspect, the analytical persona to adopt, and the exact format required by downstream tools. Which terms name these three elements?", options:["Context, perspective, and output shape","Epochs, weights, and gradients","Recall, precision, and F1","State, action, and reward"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Context, perspective, and output shape</strong> are the three elements of an effective user prompt: the evidence the model inspects, the analytical lens it adopts, and the exact format downstream tools require.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Epochs, weights, and gradients</b>: are model-training concepts, not prompt-design elements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recall, precision, and F1</b>: are evaluation metrics, not components of a user prompt.</span><span class='qd'><b>State, action, and reward</b>: are reinforcement learning components, unrelated to prompt structure.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-046", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A SOC integrates an ML model into its SIEM through an API so the model can analyze log data, correlate indicators, and auto-prioritize alerts by severity. What is the primary security operations benefit?", options:["It eliminates the need for any human analysts","It reduces analyst fatigue and improves response times through automation and scalability","It guarantees zero false positives","It removes the need to validate the model"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>It reduces analyst fatigue and improves response times through automation and scalability</strong> is the stated benefit of integrating ML into SIEM/EDR, enabling faster, more effective responses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for any human analysts</b>: automation augments analysts but does not replace human judgment.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees zero false positives</b>: models still produce false positives that require tuning and review.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need to validate the model</b>: ongoing validation remains essential for trustworthy detection.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-047", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A reinforcement learning email-triage agent's reward function includes a penalty for added latency that harms user experience. What design goal does embedding such penalties achieve?", options:["Eliminating the need for a test lab","Maximizing the number of blocked sessions regardless of impact","Cost-aware decision-making that balances security with operational continuity","Forcing the agent to ignore false positives"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Cost-aware decision-making that balances security with operational continuity</strong> is achieved because the reward function integrates penalties for actions that negatively affect user experience, teaching the agent to balance protection and usability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximizing the number of blocked sessions regardless of impact</b>: ignores user-impact penalties that the reward deliberately includes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminating the need for a test lab</b>: RL training still replays traffic in an isolated lab.</span><span class='qd'><b>Forcing the agent to ignore false positives</b>: false positives carry penalties, so the agent is taught to avoid them.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-048", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A vendor claims their rule-based system can detect any new evolving attack. Based on AI fundamentals, which statement most accurately critiques this claim?", options:["Rule-based systems learn directly from raw data without rules","Rule-based systems always outperform deep learning on novel attacks","Rule-based systems require no signatures at all","Rule-based systems are strong for known threats but machine learning and deep learning are better at detecting new, evolving patterns"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Rule-based systems are strong for known threats but machine learning and deep learning are better at detecting new, evolving patterns</strong> correctly critiques the claim, since rule-based AI excels at known threats while ML and DL handle evolving attacks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based systems always outperform deep learning on novel attacks</b>: deep learning is better at recognizing previously unseen threats.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based systems require no signatures at all</b>: they depend on predefined rules and signatures to function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based systems learn directly from raw data without rules</b>: that describes deep learning, not rule-based systems.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-049", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A team injects outliers and poisoned samples into the validation set to replicate how an attacker might probe a model's blind spots. What is this controlled adversarial simulation called?", options:["A red-team exercise","A canary deployment","Federated averaging","One-shot prompting"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A red-team exercise</strong> is the controlled adversarial simulation where outliers and poisoned samples are injected into the validation set to replicate how an attacker probes the model's blind spots.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A canary deployment</b>: gradually releases a change to a small subset and is not an adversarial poisoning test.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated averaging</b>: aggregates distributed client updates and is not an attack simulation.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-shot prompting</b>: gives a model one example and is unrelated to validation-set stress testing.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-050", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A team needs a model to extract relevant entities from unstructured incident-response reports and improve UEBA by analyzing sequences of user activity. Which technology is best suited to understanding event context and relationships?", options:["A static firewall rule","Transformers","A hash function","A downsampling routine"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Transformers</strong> improve UEBA by analyzing sequences of user activity and excel at understanding context and event relationships, making them vital for parsing reports and detecting insider threats.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A static firewall rule</b>: filters traffic by fixed criteria and cannot understand textual context or sequences.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hash function</b>: produces a fixed digest for integrity checks and does not analyze meaning or relationships.</span><span class='qd'><b>A downsampling routine</b>: discards majority-class records for balancing and is not a language-analysis technology.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-051", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"A security team is hardening its AI data pipeline. When data is first collected, what should they verify before allowing it into the training process?", options:["That the data has already been used to train another model","That the data is the largest possible volume regardless of quality","That the data is complete, accurate, and traceable to its original source","That the data is stored only in plaintext for speed"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>That the data is complete, accurate, and traceable to its original source</strong> is correct because verifying data integrity at collection safeguards against errors or manipulation that could jeopardize the AI training process.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>That the data is the largest possible volume regardless of quality</b>: volume without quality introduces noise and bias, not integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>That the data has already been used to train another model</b>: prior use is irrelevant to verifying this data's integrity and source.</span><span class='qd'><b>That the data is stored only in plaintext for speed</b>: sensitive data should be encrypted in transit and at rest, not left in plaintext.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-052", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"After verifying collected data, a team must prevent skewed or biased AI outputs caused by inconsistent records. Which step addresses this before training?", options:["Increasing the model's parameter count","Skipping preprocessing to save time","Encrypting the decryption keys alongside the data","Cleaning and standardizing the data so it is uniform"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Cleaning and standardizing the data so it is uniform</strong> prevents bias from influencing the model, because non-uniform data could skew the AI's outputs and predictions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Skipping preprocessing to save time</b>: leaves inconsistencies that skew outputs, the very problem to be solved.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the decryption keys alongside the data</b>: keys should be kept separate from the data, and this does not address bias.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the model's parameter count</b>: changes capacity but does not standardize inconsistent input data.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-053", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A team stores encrypted training data and wants to follow best practice for the decryption keys. Where should the keys be kept?", options:["In a separate, heavily secured location away from the data","In the same file as the encrypted data for convenience","Embedded in the model weights","Printed in the system prompt"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>In a separate, heavily secured location away from the data</strong> is best practice, since stored data must remain encrypted with decryption keys kept in a separate, heavily secured location.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>In the same file as the encrypted data for convenience</b>: co-locating keys with data defeats the purpose of encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Embedded in the model weights</b>: weights can be extracted or stolen, exposing the keys.</span><span class='qd'><b>Printed in the system prompt</b>: prompts can be leaked or injected, exposing the keys to attackers.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-054", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"An organization plans to share a dataset of malicious file hashes externally. What risk must they address before sharing this structured security data?", options:["Structured data cannot be shared at all under any circumstance","Improper sanitization could reveal sensitive operational techniques to attackers","Hashes are always reversible to the original files","Structured data is immune to exposure risks"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Improper sanitization could reveal sensitive operational techniques to attackers</strong> is correct because sharing a hash dataset without proper sanitization might unintentionally reveal defensive strategies, letting attackers adjust their tactics.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured data cannot be shared at all under any circumstance</b>: it can be shared if properly sanitized, so a blanket prohibition is inaccurate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hashes are always reversible to the original files</b>: cryptographic hashes are one-way; the real risk is exposing techniques, not reversal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured data is immune to exposure risks</b>: structured data carries significant exposure risk, contradicting this claim.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-055", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"An analyst worries that time-stamped firewall logs shared for AI research could help attackers. What sensitive insight can such structured, time-stamped data reveal?", options:["The model's parameter count","The exact encryption algorithm protecting the data","Corporate operating hours and shift schedules that reveal when the organization is most vulnerable","The vendor's source code"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Corporate operating hours and shift schedules that reveal when the organization is most vulnerable</strong> is correct because analyzing time-stamped logs can uncover when employees work, letting attackers time their strategies.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The exact encryption algorithm protecting the data</b>: timestamps do not disclose the encryption algorithm in use.</span><span class='qd'><b>The model's parameter count</b>: log timestamps reveal operational patterns, not model architecture details.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor's source code</b>: logs do not expose proprietary source code.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-056", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A team is auditing JSON files and email headers used to train an AI model. Why are these semi-structured sources a particular concern?", options:["They never contain sensitive information","They cannot be parsed by any tool","They are always fully unstructured","They may unintentionally embed authentication tokens or passwords in their key-value fields"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>They may unintentionally embed authentication tokens or passwords in their key-value fields</strong> is correct because semi-structured data like JSON and email headers can include secrets that must be identified and removed before use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They cannot be parsed by any tool</b>: semi-structured data is readily parsed; that is not the concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are always fully unstructured</b>: they combine structured and unstructured elements using key-value pairs.</span><span class='qd'><b>They never contain sensitive information</b>: the documented risk is exactly that they can contain embedded secrets.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-057", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A language model trained on help-desk tickets containing chat transcripts later regurgitates employee names and defensive techniques in its responses. Which data category most directly created this exposure?", options:["Unstructured data such as chat transcripts","Structured firewall logs","A cryptographic hash list","An encrypted key vault"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Unstructured data such as chat transcripts</strong> can unintentionally reveal sensitive information like employee names, system details, and defensive techniques, which a model may expose when generating responses if not carefully managed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured firewall logs</b>: are organized records and not the chat-transcript source described in the scenario.</span><span class='qd'><b>A cryptographic hash list</b>: is structured IOC data, not free-form analyst conversation.</span><span class='qd'><b>An encrypted key vault</b>: stores secrets securely and is not training data that a model would echo.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-058", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A company wants to embed invisible identifiers in its AI-generated content to establish ownership and verify the source of data throughout its lifecycle. Which technique accomplishes this?", options:["Downsampling","Watermarking","One-hot encoding","Rate limiting"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Watermarking</strong> embeds invisible identifiers within AI-generated content, creating a verifiable trail that establishes data origin, supports ownership claims, and helps track integrity across the lifecycle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Downsampling</b>: discards majority-class records to balance datasets and does not mark ownership.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-hot encoding</b>: converts categorical fields into numeric form and provides no provenance marking.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rate limiting</b>: throttles request volume and does not establish content ownership.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-059", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A developer wants to protect a proprietary model from being duplicated or reverse-engineered by competitors. Which form of watermarking specifically targets the algorithm itself?", options:["Differential privacy noise","Dataset balancing","Model watermarking using specific test prompts that produce uniquely recognizable outputs","TLS encryption in transit"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Model watermarking using specific test prompts that produce uniquely recognizable outputs</strong> safeguards models from duplication or reverse engineering by embedding prompts that yield repeatable, identifiable responses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Dataset balancing</b>: realigns class proportions in training data and does not protect a model from copying.</span><span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy noise</b>: hides individual contributions and is not a model-ownership marker.</span><span class='qd'><b>TLS encryption in transit</b>: protects data while moving but does not fingerprint the model's behavior.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-060", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A RAG system stores sensitive incident reports as embeddings in a vector index shared across departments. Which protection prevents one department from viewing another's proprietary information?", options:["Disabling audit logs","Increasing model temperature","Removing all encryption","Tenant isolation"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Tenant isolation</strong> prevents one department from accidentally or deliberately viewing another's proprietary information stored in the RAG vector index.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing model temperature</b>: raises output randomness and has no effect on data separation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing all encryption</b>: increases exposure rather than isolating tenant data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling audit logs</b>: reduces visibility and accountability, worsening security.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-061", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A team protecting a RAG deployment wants to block prompt-injection attacks before questions and documents reach the model. Which control directly addresses this?", options:["Sanitizing all questions and documents entering the system","Encrypting only the network cable","Adding more GPUs to the cluster","Increasing the number of training epochs"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Sanitizing all questions and documents entering the system</strong> blocks prompt-injection attacks before they reach the model, a unique consideration when protecting RAG storage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting only the network cable</b>: protects data in transit but does not inspect or sanitize malicious prompt content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding more GPUs to the cluster</b>: increases compute capacity and does nothing to stop injection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the number of training epochs</b>: affects training, not runtime sanitization of inputs.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-062", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"To detect even the smallest unauthorized change to an ingested dataset, a team generates a cryptographic hash for every dataset and stores the hashes in a trusted, read-only location. What does this primarily defend against?", options:["Network latency spikes","Data-poisoning attempts that skew model weights","GPU overheating","User interface bugs"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Data-poisoning attempts that skew model weights</strong> is correct because data verification via cryptographic hashing confirms the data is exactly what was approved, blocking poisoning that could bias outcomes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Network latency spikes</b>: are performance issues unrelated to dataset integrity hashing.</span><span class='qd'><b>GPU overheating</b>: is a hardware concern, not something a hash baseline detects.</span><span class='qd'><b>User interface bugs</b>: are software defects, not dataset tampering caught by hashing.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-063", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"An automated data-prep pipeline recalculates a dataset's hash on each run and fails the job if it differs from the baseline. Which tools are appropriate for generating these hashes?", options:["matplotlib and pandas","nmap and Wireshark","sha256sum on Linux or Get-FileHash in PowerShell","Jinja2 and Kafka"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>sha256sum on Linux or Get-FileHash in PowerShell</strong> are the command-line tools cited for generating cryptographic hashes to spot even the smallest changes in a dataset.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>nmap and Wireshark</b>: are network scanning and packet-capture tools, not file-hashing utilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>matplotlib and pandas</b>: are Python data-visualization and analysis libraries, not hashing tools.</span><span class='qd'><b>Jinja2 and Kafka</b>: are a templating engine and a message broker, not integrity-hashing tools.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-064", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"When auditors demand to know why an AI system reached a particular decision, two practices provide traceability: one records every transformation a dataset undergoes, the other documents its origin, licensing, and consent. Which pair is this?", options:["Rate limiting and watermarking","Pruning and quantization","Clustering and regression","Data lineage and data provenance"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Data lineage and data provenance</strong> together provide traceability: lineage records every transformation a dataset undergoes, while provenance documents its origin, licensing, and consent terms.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pruning and quantization</b>: are model-efficiency techniques, not dataset traceability practices.</span><span class='qd'><b>Clustering and regression</b>: are learning methods unrelated to documenting data history.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rate limiting and watermarking</b>: are protective controls but do not record transformations and origins.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-065", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Before using a dataset for training, an AI pipeline must scan for content that could create legal or privacy problems. Which elements should it scan for?", options:["Personally identifiable information (PII) and copyrighted material","Only the file size","Only the GPU model","Only the network port numbers"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Personally identifiable information (PII) and copyrighted material</strong> should be scanned for before use, since legal and ethical protections dictate whether a dataset can be used for training.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the file size</b>: file size has no bearing on legal or privacy compliance of the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the GPU model</b>: hardware details are irrelevant to dataset legality and privacy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the network port numbers</b>: ports relate to connectivity, not data usage rights.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-066", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A medical research consortium shares anonymized MRI scans between hospitals. The exporting hospital hashes each batch and writes the hash with a timestamp to an append-only ledger. What does this ledger primarily provide?", options:["Faster model inference at runtime","An immutable audit trail that detects corrupted or malicious files before they contaminate the model","Automatic data augmentation","Reduced parameter counts"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>An immutable audit trail that detects corrupted or malicious files before they contaminate the model</strong> is correct because the append-only ledger lets the receiver verify the signature and on-chain hash, halting processing on any mismatch.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Faster model inference at runtime</b>: ledger verification is an integrity check, not an inference speedup.</span><span class='qd'><b>Automatic data augmentation</b>: augmentation generates new examples and is unrelated to ledger hashing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduced parameter counts</b>: parameter reduction is pruning or quantization, not integrity logging.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-067", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"To help a model generalize instead of memorize, a team rotates images, flips text sequences, and adds minor random noise to create more training examples. Which technique is this, and what risk does it introduce?", options:["Pruning; it removes all sensitive data automatically","Quantization; it always doubles accuracy","Data augmentation; it can embed hidden biases or leak sensitive features if mismanaged","Clustering; it requires labeled data"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Data augmentation; it can embed hidden biases or leak sensitive features if mismanaged</strong> is correct because augmentation helps prevent overfitting but subtly alters statistical footprint and risks embedding biases or expanding the attack surface.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization; it always doubles accuracy</b>: quantization reduces precision for efficiency and does not guarantee accuracy gains.</span><span class='qd'><b>Pruning; it removes all sensitive data automatically</b>: pruning removes low-impact weights, not sensitive data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Clustering; it requires labeled data</b>: clustering is unsupervised and does not generate augmented examples.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-068", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"In intrusion-detection telemetry, benign traffic is over 99% of flows while attacks are rare, so a classifier achieves high accuracy by labeling everything 'safe.' Which technique randomly discards benign entries to address this?", options:["Watermarking","Data augmentation","Quantization","Downsampling"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Downsampling</strong> randomly discards enough benign entries to match the minority count, preventing model bias toward the majority class in imbalanced datasets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data augmentation</b>: adds more examples rather than discarding majority-class records to rebalance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization</b>: reduces numeric precision of weights and does not address class imbalance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Watermarking</b>: marks ownership and integrity and does not rebalance class proportions.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-069", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A behavioral analytics engine notices an unexpected, sudden spike in training-set size. Why is this anomaly worth flagging in the context of AI data security?", options:["It could signal a data-poisoning attempt","It always means the model is fully trained","It indicates the GPUs are idle","It confirms the data is properly encrypted"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It could signal a data-poisoning attempt</strong> is correct because behavioral analytics engines identify anomalous data flows such as an unexpected spike in training-set size that could indicate poisoning.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It always means the model is fully trained</b>: a size spike is an anomaly to investigate, not proof of completed training.</span><span class='qd'><b>It indicates the GPUs are idle</b>: dataset size has nothing to do with GPU utilization state.</span><span class='qd'><b>It confirms the data is properly encrypted</b>: a volume spike says nothing about encryption status.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-070", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"An executive asks why protecting AI training data deserves the same rigor as any other critical asset. Which statement best captures the core principle?", options:["AI tools are secure regardless of their input data","Each AI tool is only as trustworthy and secure as the data it consumes","Only the model architecture matters for security","Data protection slows AI down with no benefit"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Each AI tool is only as trustworthy and secure as the data it consumes</strong> captures the core principle, since neglecting AI data protections opens avenues for compromise ranging from model poisoning to IP theft.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>AI tools are secure regardless of their input data</b>: contradicts the principle that compromised data undermines the whole system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the model architecture matters for security</b>: data integrity is foundational, not just architecture.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data protection slows AI down with no benefit</b>: protection enables trustworthy outputs, providing clear benefit.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-071", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A team building a RAG pipeline wants to store source URL, timestamp, content hash, license, and a way to quickly remove bad data for each document. Why is capturing this provenance metadata critical?", options:["It replaces the need for encryption","It increases the model's parameter count","It can prevent tainted data from spreading into other models","It guarantees zero hallucinations"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>It can prevent tainted data from spreading into other models</strong> is correct because for LLM and RAG scenarios, saving source URL, timestamp, content hash, license, and a removal method stops tainted data from propagating.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It increases the model's parameter count</b>: provenance metadata records data history and does not change model size.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for encryption</b>: provenance complements but does not replace encryption controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees zero hallucinations</b>: provenance improves traceability but cannot eliminate hallucinations.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-072", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A SOC aggregates firewall logs from dozens of offices, but some IP addresses are logged without subnet masks or timezone metadata. What problem can this cause if the data is not cleansed?", options:["The logs become impossible to store","The data automatically becomes encrypted","The model trains faster with higher accuracy","The model may misclassify legitimate traffic as malicious lateral movement"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>The model may misclassify legitimate traffic as malicious lateral movement</strong> is correct because inconsistent records, such as missing subnet masks or timezone metadata, can cause a model to learn from noise and misclassify traffic.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The data automatically becomes encrypted</b>: missing metadata does not encrypt data; cleansing is a separate step.</span><span class='qd'><b>The model trains faster with higher accuracy</b>: dirty data degrades accuracy rather than improving it.</span><span class='qd'><b>The logs become impossible to store</b>: incomplete fields do not prevent storage; they harm model quality.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-073", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A regulated multi-party environment wants tamper-evident assurance that each data batch arrived exactly as sent. Which combination of controls supports this data integrity goal?", options:["Digital signatures plus an append-only blockchain or distributed ledger layer","Increasing temperature and top-p sampling","Downsampling and augmentation","Zero-shot and one-shot prompting"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Digital signatures plus an append-only blockchain or distributed ledger layer</strong> ensures data arrives exactly as sent, with each batch hashed and the hash written to the ledger for an immutable audit trail.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing temperature and top-p sampling</b>: are generation parameters affecting output randomness, not data integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Downsampling and augmentation</b>: are dataset-balancing and expansion techniques, not integrity verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero-shot and one-shot prompting</b>: are prompting techniques unrelated to verifying batch integrity.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-074", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"New AI-focused regulations increasingly require organizations to demonstrate where their training data came from and how systems behave after deployment. Which three needs do these requirements specifically identify?", options:["Faster GPUs, larger models, and more epochs","Data provenance controls, algorithmic transparency, and ongoing post-deployment monitoring","Plaintext storage, shared keys, and open access","Zero documentation, no audits, and no logging"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Data provenance controls, algorithmic transparency, and ongoing post-deployment monitoring</strong> are the needs new AI-focused regulatory requirements specifically identify.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Faster GPUs, larger models, and more epochs</b>: are performance choices, not regulatory data-governance requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Plaintext storage, shared keys, and open access</b>: are insecure practices that regulations discourage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero documentation, no audits, and no logging</b>: directly conflict with transparency and monitoring obligations.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-075", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"An image classifier is used to analyze photos of secure facilities. Why does this unstructured-data use case pose a security risk?", options:["Images contain no exploitable information","Image classifiers cannot process photographs","It might inadvertently disclose facility layout or security capabilities that could be exploited","Classifiers automatically encrypt all images"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>It might inadvertently disclose facility layout or security capabilities that could be exploited</strong> is correct because image classifiers analyzing photos of buildings or secure areas can reveal important details about a facility's defenses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Image classifiers cannot process photographs</b>: processing photographs is exactly what image classifiers do.</span><span class='qd'><b>Images contain no exploitable information</b>: images can reveal sensitive facility details, contradicting this claim.</span><span class='qd'><b>Classifiers automatically encrypt all images</b>: classification categorizes images and does not encrypt them.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-076", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"An organization is formalizing security across its AI program. According to the AI lifecycle, which phase comes first, where architects align desired outcomes with risk appetite and perform threat modeling?", options:["Model Deployment/Integration","Operation/Inference","Monitoring and Maintenance","Design"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Design</strong> begins the lifecycle, where business value and risk appetite intersect and architects perform threat modeling and identify compliance obligations before later phases.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Operation/Inference</b>: is where the system generates value at runtime, well after design.</span><span class='qd'><b>Monitoring and Maintenance</b>: completes the lifecycle through retraining and oversight, not the start.</span><span class='qd'><b>Model Deployment/Integration</b>: occurs after a model is trained, not at the outset.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-077", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"During the data collection and preparation phase, a team wants to examine a dataset for outliers that could signal poisoning before training begins. Which type of tooling supports this?", options:["An adversarial robustness toolbox that inspects datasets for poisoning indicators","A spreadsheet of vendor contacts","A network bandwidth monitor","A password manager"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>An adversarial robustness toolbox that inspects datasets for poisoning indicators</strong> is correct because such tools make it possible to examine a dataset for outliers that could signal poisoning before training begins.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet of vendor contacts</b>: tracks relationships and does not analyze datasets for poisoning.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network bandwidth monitor</b>: measures traffic throughput, not dataset integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A password manager</b>: stores credentials and is unrelated to detecting poisoned training data.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-078", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"In the model development and training phase, a team performs dependency scanning of ML frameworks, ensures reproducible builds, and isolates training networks. What threat are these practices primarily meant to prevent?", options:["Physical theft of laptops","Supply-chain attacks","Email spam","Phishing of executives"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Supply-chain attacks</strong> are prevented through dependency scanning of ML frameworks, reproducible builds, and isolated training networks during model development.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical theft of laptops</b>: is mitigated by device controls, not dependency scanning of frameworks.</span><span class='qd'><b>Email spam</b>: is handled by mail filtering, unrelated to build reproducibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Phishing of executives</b>: is addressed by awareness and email controls, not training-network isolation.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-079", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"Before going live, a team validates a new detection model's predictions against a reference environment under production-level traffic using a gradual rollout. Which deployment strategies fit this goal?", options:["Federated averaging","K-fold cross-validation","Blue-green rollout or canary release","Quantization-aware training"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Blue-green rollout or canary release</strong> validates model predictions against a reference environment so detection rates stay consistent under production-level traffic during the deployment and integration phase.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>K-fold cross-validation</b>: is an evaluation method used during development, not a production rollout strategy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated averaging</b>: aggregates distributed training updates and is not a deployment validation approach.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization-aware training</b>: preserves accuracy while reducing precision and is unrelated to staged rollout.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-080", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"During the operation and inference phase, runtime monitoring watches for features that drift beyond training distributions and spikes in inference latency. What might a sudden latency spike indicate?", options:["A reduced parameter count","Successful model watermarking","Completed data augmentation","A denial-of-service attack"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>A denial-of-service attack</strong> is what spikes in inference latency could indicate during the operation phase, alongside watching for feature drift and unexpected calls to infrequently used elements.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Successful model watermarking</b>: embeds ownership identifiers and does not cause latency spikes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Completed data augmentation</b>: occurs during data preparation, not inference-time latency monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reduced parameter count</b>: results from pruning and would tend to speed up, not spike, inference.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-081", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"In the monitoring and maintenance phase, a team collects false positives, analyst annotations, and post-incident reports and channels them back to data preparation. What does this make the AI lifecycle?", options:["A process of continuous improvement rather than a linear process","A one-time linear deployment with no feedback","A purely manual workflow with no automation","An offline system disconnected from operations"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A process of continuous improvement rather than a linear process</strong> is correct because secure feedback pipelines route false positives, annotations, and reports back to data preparation for ongoing retraining.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A one-time linear deployment with no feedback</b>: contradicts the feedback loops that drive continuous improvement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A purely manual workflow with no automation</b>: the lifecycle integrates automated pipelines and retraining.</span><span class='qd'><b>An offline system disconnected from operations</b>: feedback comes directly from operational incidents and alerts.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-082", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"An attacker launches a denial-of-service against an AI pipeline's traffic-collection endpoints so little data is sent. Why is this dangerous for downstream analytics?", options:["It immediately encrypts all collected data","The resulting silence may be misread as legitimate inactivity, tricking analytics to redefine 'normal'","It improves the model's accuracy on attacks","It has no effect because models ignore missing data"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>The resulting silence may be misread as legitimate inactivity, tricking analytics to redefine 'normal'</strong> is correct because a DoS that starves the pipeline can cause downstream analytics to wrongly treat the absence of data as normal traffic.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It immediately encrypts all collected data</b>: a DoS disrupts collection; it does not encrypt data.</span><span class='qd'><b>It improves the model's accuracy on attacks</b>: starving the pipeline degrades, not improves, detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>It has no effect because models ignore missing data</b>: missing data can skew the learned baseline, so it does have an effect.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-083", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"To distinguish a true lull in traffic from data that is stalled or delayed during a possible DoS, what defensive measure helps the ingest layer?", options:["Removing redundant sensors to simplify the design","Disabling all logging to save bandwidth","Exchanging cryptographically signed heartbeat messages with sequence numbers and expiry","Trusting any data that arrives without verification"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Exchanging cryptographically signed heartbeat messages with sequence numbers and expiry</strong> helps the ingest layer distinguish a true lull from stalled or delayed data, alongside rate-limiting and redundant sensors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all logging to save bandwidth</b>: removes the forensic visibility needed to detect manipulation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing redundant sensors to simplify the design</b>: redundancy is recommended, so removing it weakens detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusting any data that arrives without verification</b>: contradicts the tamper-evident, signed approach required.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-084", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"To detect attackers who flood the pipeline with bogus records that gradually shift a model's decision threshold, a team inserts inputs with known expected outputs into the stream. What does an unexplained drift in these outcomes indicate?", options:["The data is now fully anonymized","The model has finished training successfully","The GPUs need replacement","The training distribution is under attack"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>The training distribution is under attack</strong> is correct because reference inputs with known outputs are seeded so that if their outcomes drift without a legitimate business reason, the system flags a poisoning attack.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The model has finished training successfully</b>: drift in known-output references signals attack, not completion.</span><span class='qd'><b>The GPUs need replacement</b>: outcome drift reflects data manipulation, not hardware failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data is now fully anonymized</b>: anonymization is unrelated to drift in seeded reference outputs.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-085", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"An organization establishes an auditable system of record for model, dataset, and evaluation versions, plus a formal change-control process for AI changes affecting security posture. What is this system called?", options:["A model registry","A vector index","A reward table","A confusion matrix"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A model registry</strong> is an auditable system of record for model, dataset, and evaluation versions, supporting formal change control that ensures provenance, accountability, and safe operation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A vector index</b>: stores embeddings for retrieval and is not a versioned record of models and datasets.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reward table</b>: maps situations to actions in reinforcement learning, not a model-version record.</span><span class='qd'><b>A confusion matrix</b>: summarizes classification results and is not a system of record for versions.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-086", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"Before promoting a high-impact detection model to production, an organization requires documented approvals from the SOC manager, model owner, and risk owner, plus defined change windows and rollback plans. What is the primary purpose of these controls?", options:["To speed deployment by removing all oversight","To ensure provenance, accountability, and safe operation of AI-assisted security","To eliminate the need for monitoring","To reduce the model's parameter count"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>To ensure provenance, accountability, and safe operation of AI-assisted security</strong> is the purpose of requiring documented human approvals, change windows, active monitoring, and rollback plans for high-impact promotions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To speed deployment by removing all oversight</b>: these controls add oversight, not remove it.</span><span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for monitoring</b>: active monitoring is explicitly required during promotion.</span><span class='qd'><b>To reduce the model's parameter count</b>: change control governs approvals, not model size.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-087", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"An automated system flags a domain as suspicious and is about to block it, but an analyst knows the company is mid-merger and needs that site. Which security concept lets the analyst intervene at this decision point?", options:["Concept drift","Fully autonomous remediation","Human-in-the-loop","Quantization"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Human-in-the-loop</strong> emphasizes having a qualified analyst step in at crucial decision points so automated systems do not take critical actions without oversight, letting context like a merger inform the choice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fully autonomous remediation</b>: would block the domain without the human judgment the scenario requires.</span><span class='qd'><b>Concept drift</b>: describes changing data over time, not a human intervention point.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantization</b>: reduces model numeric precision and is unrelated to decision oversight.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-088", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Rather than reviewing each individual decision, a governance team continually monitors a model's overall behavior, reviewing performance dashboards and audit logs, and can suspend automated actions when anomalies arise. Which function is this?", options:["Federated learning","Human-in-the-loop","Data augmentation","Human oversight"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Human oversight</strong> operates at a broader level, continually monitoring the model's behavior through dashboards and audit logs and suspending automated actions until confidence is restored.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Human-in-the-loop</b>: focuses on intervening at individual critical decisions, not broad behavioral monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data augmentation</b>: generates training examples and is not an oversight function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated learning</b>: is a distributed training method, not a monitoring role.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-089", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A team periodically feeds known malicious and benign emails into a phishing classifier to confirm it responds as expected and to uncover blind spots from data drift. Which human function does this describe?", options:["Human validation","Human oversight","Human-in-the-loop","Secure aggregation"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Human validation</strong> independently samples model outputs and compares them to expectations through expert review or controlled testing, uncovering blind spots from data drift and informing retraining.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Human oversight</b>: continuously monitors overall behavior rather than independently testing with known samples.</span><span class='qd'><b>Human-in-the-loop</b>: intervenes at live decision points, not periodic independent validation testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Secure aggregation</b>: protects federated update privacy and is not a validation function.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-090", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"An organization defines three structured response levels for AI-driven security actions. Which set correctly lists them?", options:["Train, Validate, and Test","Detect-Only, Auto-Remediate, and Human-Approve","Encrypt, Hash, and Sign","Zero-shot, One-shot, and Multi-shot"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Detect-Only, Auto-Remediate, and Human-Approve</strong> are the three response levels reflecting human-centric AI design, ranging from monitoring without action to automated remediation to requiring human validation for risky actions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Train, Validate, and Test</b>: are data-partition stages, not response levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt, Hash, and Sign</b>: are data-protection operations, not response tiers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero-shot, One-shot, and Multi-shot</b>: are prompting techniques, not response levels.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-091", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"For critical AI-driven actions that could cause substantial operational impact, an organization requires two authorized people to approve before execution. Which control is this?", options:["Differential privacy","A canary release","A two-person rule","One-hot encoding"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>A two-person rule</strong> should be enforced for critical actions that could result in substantial operational impacts, ensuring no single person can execute a high-risk AI-driven action alone.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A canary release</b>: gradually rolls out a change to a subset and is not a dual-approval control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Differential privacy</b>: adds noise to protect individuals and is unrelated to approval workflows.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-hot encoding</b>: converts categorical data to numeric form and is not an authorization control.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-092", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"When an AI system's decision confidence drops or the correct next step is unclear, what fail-safe behavior should the design enforce?", options:["Delete the model and retrain from scratch","Automatically execute the highest-impact action available","Disable all logging immediately","Switch to monitor-only mode until a human can intervene"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Switch to monitor-only mode until a human can intervene</strong> is the fail-safe behavior when decision confidence decreases or next steps are unclear, preventing risky automated actions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Automatically execute the highest-impact action available</b>: acting aggressively under low confidence is exactly what fail-safes prevent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable all logging immediately</b>: logging must continue for accountability, not be disabled.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete the model and retrain from scratch</b>: an overreaction that disrupts operations rather than safely pausing.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-093", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"To maintain accountability for AI-driven security, all actions requiring approval must be documented and tamper-evident. Why is the tamper-evident requirement important?", options:["It preserves a trustworthy record so approvals cannot be secretly altered after the fact","It speeds up model inference","It removes the need for human approvers","It increases the training dataset size"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It preserves a trustworthy record so approvals cannot be secretly altered after the fact</strong> is correct because actions requiring approvals must be documented and tamper-evident to support accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It speeds up model inference</b>: tamper-evident logging is about integrity of records, not inference speed.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for human approvers</b>: it documents approver actions; it does not eliminate approvers.</span><span class='qd'><b>It increases the training dataset size</b>: audit records are not training data expansion.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-094", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"To define clear accountability in AI oversight, an organization assigns distinct roles. Which role is responsible for the overall integrity of the AI system?", options:["The risk owner","The model owner","The data labeler","The end user"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>The model owner</strong> is responsible for the overall integrity of the AI system, while other roles handle risk and ethical alignment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The risk owner</b>: focuses on identifying and mitigating potential risks, not overall system integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data labeler</b>: annotates training data and does not own the system's integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The end user</b>: consumes the system's outputs and is not accountable for its integrity.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-095", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"To keep AI oversight unbiased, how should the oversight function relate to the teams that build the AI systems?", options:["It should report directly to the model developers","It should be performed by the same engineers who built the model","It must function independently from those who build the systems","It should be eliminated to reduce overhead"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>It must function independently from those who build the systems</strong> is correct because oversight must operate independently to provide an unbiased balance in management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It should be performed by the same engineers who built the model</b>: that creates conflicts of interest and bias.</span><span class='qd'><b>It should report directly to the model developers</b>: reporting into the builders undermines independence.</span><span class='qd'><b>It should be eliminated to reduce overhead</b>: removing oversight defeats accountability and governance.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-096", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"An automated system recommends quarantining a server, but the SOC analyst knows it processes critical vendor payments due within hours. How does keeping a human in the loop best resolve this tension?", options:["The analyst should delete the server's logs to stop the alert","The analyst should always defer to the automated quarantine recommendation","The analyst should disable the detection system permanently","The analyst can investigate the activity while keeping the server operational, avoiding a payment outage"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>The analyst can investigate the activity while keeping the server operational, avoiding a payment outage</strong> is correct because human-in-the-loop lets the analyst apply contextual knowledge for a nuanced response that balances security and business continuity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The analyst should always defer to the automated quarantine recommendation</b>: blind deference ignores critical business context and could cause an outage.</span><span class='qd'><b>The analyst should disable the detection system permanently</b>: that removes valuable detection capability entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>The analyst should delete the server's logs to stop the alert</b>: destroying logs harms investigation and accountability.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-097", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"A human-centric AI governance program schedules monthly performance reviews and quarterly fairness checks. What is the purpose of the quarterly fairness checks?", options:["To validate that the system remains impartial and unbiased","To increase the model's parameter count","To reduce encryption strength over time","To eliminate the need for monitoring dashboards"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>To validate that the system remains impartial and unbiased</strong> is the purpose of quarterly fairness checks, complementing monthly performance reviews in a defined audit cadence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To increase the model's parameter count</b>: fairness checks evaluate bias, not model size.</span><span class='qd'><b>To reduce encryption strength over time</b>: weakening encryption is never a governance goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for monitoring dashboards</b>: dashboards remain essential alongside fairness checks.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-098", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"To address regulatory requirements for explainability and accountability, a supervisory layer can suspend automated actions when the model suddenly flags a benign internal application as malicious after a software update. Which function represents this layer?", options:["Reinforcement learning reward shaping","Human oversight as organizational governance","Data downsampling","Vector index encryption"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Human oversight as organizational governance</strong> represents the supervisory layer that suspends automated actions during anomalies and establishes a formal escalation pathway for explainability and accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reinforcement learning reward shaping</b>: tunes an agent's incentives and is not a governance escalation layer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data downsampling</b>: rebalances training classes and is unrelated to suspending automated actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vector index encryption</b>: protects RAG storage and does not provide supervisory governance.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-099", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"An organization defines criteria for emergency-stop controls in its AI security program. What is the primary purpose of these controls?", options:["To replace human analysts entirely","To automatically increase the model's autonomy over time","To support immediate intervention if the system operates outside acceptable parameters or poses unanticipated risks","To speed up data augmentation"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>To support immediate intervention if the system operates outside acceptable parameters or poses unanticipated risks</strong> is the purpose of emergency-stop controls in a human-centric design.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To automatically increase the model's autonomy over time</b>: emergency stops constrain risky behavior, not expand autonomy.</span><span class='qd'><b>To replace human analysts entirely</b>: these controls keep humans empowered to intervene, not remove them.</span><span class='qd'><b>To speed up data augmentation</b>: augmentation is a data step unrelated to emergency stops.</span>" },
  { id:"D1-100", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A CISO summarizes how the three human functions work together across the AI lifecycle. Which statement best describes their combined value?", options:["They apply only during the design phase and nowhere else","All three functions are interchangeable and perform the same task","They eliminate the need for any automation in security","Human-in-the-loop mitigates immediate risk, oversight ensures long-term alignment, and validation ensures statistical confidence becomes real-world reliability"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Human-in-the-loop mitigates immediate risk, oversight ensures long-term alignment, and validation ensures statistical confidence becomes real-world reliability</strong> correctly describes how the three functions form a layered defense balancing machine efficiency with human judgment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>All three functions are interchangeable and perform the same task</b>: each plays a distinct role, so they are not interchangeable.</span><span class='qd'><b>They eliminate the need for any automation in security</b>: they complement automation rather than replace it.</span><span class='qd'><b>They apply only during the design phase and nowhere else</b>: they operate throughout the lifecycle, not just at design.</span>" }
);
